Of course, in standard lattice gauge theory, the properties mentioned
so far are much easier to verify in direct computations. The category
theoretic language presented here, however, provides a structural
framework which would have allowed us to derive all these properties
in a systematic fashion even if we had not known them in advance. We
will exploit this conceptual advantage when we generalize lattice
gauge theory to the next level, colouring both edges and faces with
dynamical variables. In Section , we will
encounter the higher level analogues of all the diagrams used here.
Without any help from category theory it would hardly be possible to
guess the appropriate assignment of variables and the relevant
symmetries.

Our plan for the following section is to review suitable generalizations
for the notions of category, functor and natural transformation in
order to pass on to the next level, including interesting examples for
which we can perform explicit computations. The higher level
generalizations are known as -categories, -functors, .



Mathematical background 




The Eckmann-Hilton argument 



 
 

  (a) Horizontal composition of faces is denoted by a dot
  (). (b) Vertical composition is indicated by a little circle
  () which is read from left to right in our equations. (c)
  Parentheses are not necessary provided the exchange
  law eq_exchange  holds. 

Let us first review the argument of Eckmann and Hilton which explains why we are forced to use Abelian groups as long as we
colour only the faces.

We assume that the plaquettes of the lattice are labeled by the
elements  of some algebraic structure . We further assume
that there are two composition laws as illustrated in
Figure . Horizontal composition  is denoted by
a dot (), vertical composition  by a circle
(). Finally, we assume that both compositions have two-sided
units, denoted by  and . On larger lattices, there
will occur mixed compositions such as that shown in
Figure (c). We require that this composition is well
defined without parentheses,  it does not depend on the ordering
by which horizontal and vertical compositions are performed. This
means that the exchange law ,
 
is satisfied.

This implies first that the units actually agree because
 
Therefore we can write . The exchange law further
implies that both compositions agree because for any ,
 
and finally that this composition is Abelian,
) 
Drawing the diagrams corresponding to eq_abelian) , it becomes
obvious that the two-dimensionality of the situation allows  and
 to move around in the plane and thereby to change places.

If we wish to escape this Abelianness, we have to change some of the
initial assumptions. There are a priori)  various conceivable
approaches. Since we aim for a setting similar to lattice gauge
theory, we have to require that Figure (c) is
well-defined without parentheses so that the exchange
law eq_exchange)  is not in question. It turns out that it is a
viable strategy to colour both edges and faces with different
algebraic structures in such a way that there is a non-trivial
interplay and that the identities no longer agree.

An observation related to the Eckmann-Hilton argument was made
independently by Teitelboim  in a physical context. The
idea is as follows. In conventional gauge theory, there is the notion
of a 'path ordered product' by which one defines the parallel
transport along some curve and which is independent of the
parameterization and thus a geometrical quantity. At higher level,
however, one is forced to use Abelian labels because it seems to be
impossible to define a 'surface ordered product' for generic
non-Abelian quantities in a way that is independent of the choice of
coordinates.


Lie -groups) 


In order to sidestep the Eckmann-Hilton argument, we follow ideas
from higher category theory as explained in . The picture
is as follows. The edges, going from one vertex to another, are
labeled with elements  from one algebraic
structure. Composition of edges has to be reflected in this algebraic
structure,
 
We therefore require an associative product . In
addition to this, there are faces, going from one edge to another,
which are labeled with elements  from another algebraic
structure. Here we use bi-gons  as the fundamental faces, 
their boundary consists of only two edges that have the same source
and target vertex,
 
These bi-gons can then be composed horizontally,
 
and vertically,
 
The mixed composition,
 
is required to be independent of the ordering of the horizontal and
vertical compositions which is precisely stated by the exchange law,
 

Lie -groups as introduced by Baez  form a suitable
structure with these properties. Note that the Eckmann-Hilton
argument can be avoided here because we have labeled the edges by
 and we perform some sort of computation 
whenever edges are composed. The units for the vertical composition
() will in general depend on the  and therefore need not
agree. When we list examples below, we mention in which cases the
Eckmann-Hilton argument applies and in which it does not.

Strict Lie -groups can be obtained by a standard construction in
category theory. A strict Lie -group is an internal category 
in the category of Lie groups. This means that we take the definition
of a small category (Definition ) and systematically
replace the word 'set' by 'Lie group' and 'map' by 'Lie group
homomorphism'.

 
