Suitable -categories 


We have already seen that Lie -groups provide two compositions with
the required identities such that the relevant diagrams
( eq_mixed ) can be drawn and such that the Eckmann-Hilton
argument can be avoided. Before we can generalize the constructions of
Section , however, we need higher level analogues
of category, functor and natural equivalence. We therefore have to
climb up by one level and introduce the notion of -categories.

A -category  is a category 'enriched in Cat',  for
each pair of objects , we have now a category 
rather than just the set of all morphisms . The objects in
 are the morphisms of  and the morphisms of
 are new data. They are called -morphisms . The
definition of Mac Lane  is of this type. We restrict
ourselves to the strict  case,  equalities of morphisms are
satisfied exactly and are not weakened  to hold only up to
-isomorphism. For more details on -categories, see Chapter XII.3
of  and . In the following, we remove one level
of abstraction from this definition and write down the conditions in
detail.

 
