Notice that we have labeled the - and -cells (edges and faces)
of the lattice with data from the -groupoid , but
that the -action is defined one level higher, namely for the
-cells (tetrahedra). So far we have not formally defined the
notion of a tetrahedron. For our purposes it is sufficient that the
preceding definition can be used whenever we have a collection of four
triangles whose edges match as shown in Figure .

In standard lattice gauge theory, the action is a character of the
holonomy around a loop. In our generalized setting, it turns out that,
for our -holonomy, we need the following two invariances in order
to obtain a locally -gauge invariant action.

 
