Examples and physical applications 



In this section, we come back to some examples of strict Lie
-groups (Example ), illustrate what the admissible
gauge invariant -actions are and sketch possible applications.

 
The trivial -group (see Example (1)). In this case
the assignment of variables reduces to conventional lattice gauge
theory. There are no labels at the faces, and the local gauge
transformations (Example ) reduce to the ordinary ones
(Example ). As there are no variables associated
with the faces, -actions are useless in this case.

 
The purely Abelian -group (see Example (2)). In
this case, the edges are not labeled while the faces are labeled with
elements of some Abelian group . We have . If we choose
, we recover -form electrodynamics. Possible -actions
are real characters of ,  for  they are of the form
 for some , and our model agrees
with that of  for  except that it is defined on
triangulations rather than on hyper-cubic lattices.

 
The Euclidean -groups (see Example (4)). Again we
have . The allowed -actions are functions of the
-invariant norm,  of the form 
for some function . This resembles the expansors used
in  in the case of the Poincare -group.

Observe that this example is a non-trivial generalization of -form
electrodynamics even though  is Abelian. There is a non-trivial
interplay with  which requires the -action to be constant on the
orbits of  on . For the Poincare -group, this example
suggests the following more ambitious conjecture.

 
Lattice -gauge theory using the Poincare -group in four
dimensions with a suitable action is equivalent to the refined
Barrett-Crane-Yetter state sum proposed in  in the
same fashion as standard lattice gauge theory with -function
Boltzmann weight is related to the Ooguri model, see, for
example .

Lattice -gauge theory should therefore be formulated on the
-complex dual to the triangulation used in the state sum model so
that we can apply a suitable harmonic analysis and obtain sums over
representations of  for the edges and sums over representations of
 for the faces of the triangulation. This way it might be possible
to obtain further conditions on the measure used in the state sum
model and to relate it to a classical action with constraints at the
classical level.

 
The automorphism -group of a simple compact Lie group  (see
Example (5)). In this case  is the
centre of  and any function  gives rise to a
-action. This example can be understood as a lattice model of the
connections on non-Abelian gerbes. We notice some coincidences which
suggest the following conjecture.

 
Lattice -gauge theory with the automorphism -group for
,   and , describes some
aspects of the collective phenomena of strongly coupled pure QCD. In
fact, the -gauge invariant expressions of
Theorem  resemble the observables that detect centre
monopoles and vortices which seem to play a key role in the
understanding of the confinement of static quarks in pure lattice QCD.



Discussion and outlook 




Technical questions 


At the technical level, there are a number of natural questions to
ask. What is the most general gauge invariant expression? In standard
lattice gauge theory, these are spin networks  ,
generalizations of Wilson loops that include branchings of the lines
with intertwiners of the gauge group at the branching points. In order
to fully understand the possible spin networks, one has to study the
representation category of the gauge group. In our lattice -gauge
theory, the expressions  of Theorem are the analogues of Wilson loops. The most general gauge invariant
expressions will be given by coloured branched surfaces,  by some
sort of spin foams  . In order to understand these
spin foams, we have to study the representation -category of a Lie
-group. Work on the representation theory of -groups is in
progress . It is desirable to find a gauge
invariant expression which combines both holonomies of morphisms
around loops and -holonomies around closed surfaces so that this
expression reduces to the Wilson action if we choose the trivial
-group. At the moment we have either the old observables
(characters of holonomies) which are not -gauge invariant or very
special new ones (-actions of -holonomies) which disappear for
the trivial -group.

A related question is that of a maximal gauge fixing. In standard
lattice gauge theory, one can gauge fix all edges of a spanning tree
to be labeled by the group unit. In lattice -gauge theory, the
gauge fixing will make use of suitable surfaces.

A further technical observation is that for -categories, there is
one more natural type of maps besides functors and pseudo-natural
transformations. These are called modifications  and relate two
natural transformations. 

 
Let ,  be small strict -categories,
 be strict -functors and
 be pseudo-natural
transformations. A quasi-modification 
 is a map
 assigning to each object
 a -morphism 
in  such that,
 
holds for each -morphism  in 
where  are morphisms in . This is
illustrated by the following diagram,
 
We have suppressed the double arrows for the following -morphisms
in order to keep the diagram simple,
 2 
  _g          &F_g _y   
    && _xF_g ,

  _g^   &F_g^ _y   
    && _xF_g^ ,

  _g        &F_g _y 
    && _xF_g ,

  _g^ &F_g^ _y 
    && _xF_g^ .

It is open what modifications mean physically. Are some gauge
equivalent configurations 'more equal' than others? An explanation why
we are not forced to use this additional structural level may be the
fact that our action is a map into the real numbers as opposed to a
map into some -category. The requirement to use real numbers is, of
course, imposed by the physical framework, but the -categorical
treatment might indicate that one should try to categorify the action
or the path integral.

Given a path integral formulation of lattice -gauge theory as
sketched in Section , we have the
connection picture  of this theory which is given in terms of
continuous variables. It is known that for lattice -theory (see,
for example ) and also for standard lattice
Yang-Mills theory , there is an equivalent
dual  formulation provided by the representation picture 
which is, in the case of Yang-Mills theory, the corresponding
strong-weak dual theory. The dual formulation of standard lattice
gauge theory is a spin foam model. How does the dual formulation of
lattice -gauge theory look like?

It is already obvious that we have to understand the representation
-category of the gauge -group in order to formulate such a
model. If our lattice -gauge theory lives on the two-complex dual
to some triangulation of a given four-manifold, the dual theory will
involve sums over suitable vector spaces for all edges and for all
faces of the original triangulation. As already mentioned, this is
precisely the structure of the refined Barrett-Crane-Yetter state
sum model of quantum gravity as proposed in . An
interesting project is therefore to perform the harmonic expansion
(better: -harmonic expansion) of the Lie -group valued variables
and, for generic -action, to generalize the transformation
of  to lattice -gauge theory. We emphasize that
the dual theory will involve one higher level of the given simplicial
complex because the -action is associated with the -simplices.

Thinking about the representation picture of lattice -gauge theory,
the entire program of the lattice gauge and state sum models is worth
reconsidering: topological models, diagrammatic techniques
generalizing the chain mail  and generalizing the ribbon
diagrammatics of . What is a suitable
'non-commutative' structure which generalizes the ribbon diagrams
of  and maybe weakens the axioms of the
-category used? For weak versions of -groups, see . A
general framework for state sum invariants of four-manifolds is
provided by Mackaay's construction .


A hierarchy of theories 


One of the key ideas of higher category theory is that there is a
hierarchy of structures (sets, categories, -categories,
). In this hierarchy, we call standard lattice gauge theory a
-gauge theory  and the model constructed in the present
article a -gauge theory . Lattice -gauge theory is beyond
the scope of this study, but we can still consider lattice -gauge
theory in order to learn more about the hierarchy of models.

Consider the construction of Section . How does it
collapse in the case of a -gauge theory? The lattice is a
-category,  just a set, a collection of points without
structure. Similarly the set of labels ('-gauge group'). A
configuration is then a -functor which is just a map from the set
of points to the -gauge group. There is no notion of natural
equivalence and therefore no local symmetry. Such a model resembles a
lattice spin model. These models include the lattice versions of
non-linear sigma models. In total, we have the following information
on the hierarchy of lattice -gauge theories.

. No local symmetry. The variables are associated with the
vertices and the action terms with the edges. Gauge 'invariant'
quantities are arbitrary functions. For models with a certain global
symmetry, the strong coupling expansion  is an expansion in
terms of spin networks (coloured graphs) and the dual formulation is a
spin network model.

. Standard lattice gauge theory. The variables are associated
with the edges and the action terms with the faces. Gauge invariant
quantities are spin networks. The strong coupling
expansion  is an expansion in terms of spin foams
(coloured -complexes) and the dual model is a spin foam model.

. The model constructed in the present article. The generic gauge
invariant quantities are certain spin foams. From the assignment of
variables one can already see that the strong coupling expansion will
lead to coloured -complexes.

It seems that we can minimally couple the model at level  with the
model at . The classic example at  is the Abelian Higgs
model with frozen radial mode , but this construction can
be extended to non-Abelian symmetry groups as well . The
next more general step would therefore be to couple a -gauge theory
to standard lattice gauge theory.


General comments 


It is an interesting question whether one can construct a Topological
Quantum Field Theory (TQFT) from our -gauge theory. We should
therefore require the higher level analogue of the flatness condition
in order to obtain topological invariants. This means we should
restrict the partition function of our quantum theory to those
configurations for which the -holonomy  vanishes at
every tetrahedron . This is the zero -curvature
condition .

For certain finite crossed modules this TQFT was constructed by
Yetter  using the language of categorical groups, 
group objects in the category of groupoids. In the topological case
one can choose an arbitrary triangulation as the lattice and then
construct the infinite refinement limit. This means in physical terms
that the TQFT has a trivial renormalization.

The continuum counterpart of the higher lattice gauge theory was
developed in  and, for non-Abelian gerbes,
in . In the continuum, it has turned out to be difficult to
find fully gauge invariant actions. In the discrete approach, however,
see also , invariant actions arise naturally from the
tetrahedron diagram, Figure . Our result is that
the admissible -actions are sensitive only to , an
observation which may help to better understand the continuum
situation. In particular for the automorphism -group,  is
often a discrete group. In this case, it will be impossible to write
down a naive continuum expression for the -action which just uses
Lie algebras instead of Lie groups. Continuum -actions will rather
involve some kind of topological defect or singularity and will be
given by non-local expressions similar to topological charges.

It should generally be possible to consider 'infinitesimal' simplices
as in  in order to infer the continuum formulas
corresponding to the given discrete expressions. It is open whether
the converse is possible,  to integrate the differential continuum
expressions in order to recover the non-infinitesimal formulas. The
problem is that there is no 'surface ordered product' available
yet. Because of this obstacle, we favour the discrete approach, at
least for now.

Finally, the model constructed here together with the continuum
counterparts developed in  demonstrates that there
exist theories with local symmetries beyond conventional gauge
theory. Are the corresponding quantum field theories relevant in
nature? We have indicated two possible areas of physics in which they
might turn out to be useful, state sum models of quantum gravity and
the low energy behaviour of QCD.




